{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"97997560-7e97-4e33-8d57-76b891c57649","content":"The project file doesn't exist yet at that path, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport (the standard for VS Code agent mode):\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command`/`args`** — runs `dotnet run` pointing at your `.csproj`.\n- Your server must read JSON-RPC from **stdin** and write responses to **stdout** (use a library like `ModelContextProtocol` or `McpDotNet`).\n- Make sure any logging goes to **stderr**, not stdout, to avoid corrupting the protocol stream.\n\nFor a **published** build (faster startup), use:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"src/MyMcpServer/bin/Release/net8.0/MyMcpServer.dll\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"312eeb2c-ff07-4bec-8336-62f76f1f3901","outputTokens":355,"requestId":"385F:29F7F6:6AD52BA:7342FF7:6A03CFAD"},"id":"fc6a81fa-200a-4a90-9b27-770f491a031a","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:11:19.132Z","parentId":"ff39d7ec-237e-4810-a45e-7974c3d19e72"}
